# Documentation and Changelog Rules

## Documentation is part of the deliverable
All meaningful architectural, protocol, or public SDK changes should be documented.

## Keep aligned
When changing behavior, update whichever of these are relevant:
- protocol docs
- function catalog
- error taxonomy
- capability matrix
- emulator scenario docs
- MCP docs
- partner integration guides
- changelog

## Public change expectations
Document:
- what changed
- why it changed
- whether it is breaking, additive, or internal
- any migration implications
- any new test scenarios

## Changelog guidance
Track at minimum:
- protocol version changes
- SDK changes by platform
- emulator scenario additions or behavior changes
- MCP tool/resource changes
- known limitations and fixes

## Partner empathy rule
Assume a partner engineer is integrating under time pressure.
Documentation should help them understand:
- the supported flows
- the required fields
- error behavior
- recovery behavior
- how to test safely

## Do not
- leave public behavior undocumented
- add hidden operational requirements
- assume internal tribal knowledge is sufficient
